{|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship image | Ship image = | Ship caption = }} {{Infobox ship career | Hide header = | Ship country = United States | Ship flag ={{USN flag|1925}} | Ship name = ''Cotopaxi'' | Ship namesake = [[Cotopaxi]] | Ship owner = [[Clinchfield Navigation Company]] | Ship operator = | Ship registry = | Ship route = | Ship ordered = | Ship builder = [[Great Lakes Engineering Works]], [[Ecorse, Michigan]] | Ship original cost = | Ship yard number = 209 | Ship way number = | Ship laid down = | Ship launched = 1918 | Ship completed = | Ship christened = | Ship acquired = | Ship maiden voyage = | Ship in service = | Ship out of service = On or after 1 December 1925 | Ship identification = {{IMO|217270}} | Ship fate = Reported missing, 1 December 1925 | Ship status = | Ship notes = }} {{Infobox ship characteristics | Hide header = | Header caption = | Ship class = | Ship tonnage = {{GRT|2351}} | Ship displacement = | Ship length = {{cvt|253|ft}} | Ship beam = {{cvt|44|ft}} | Ship height = | Ship draught = | Ship draft = {{cvt|25|ft}} | Ship depth = | Ship decks = | Ship deck clearance = | Ship ramps = | Ship ice class = | Ship sail plan = | Ship power = [[Steam boiler]] | Ship propulsion = *[[Triple expansion engine]] * 1 × [[Propeller|screw]] | Ship speed = {{convert|9.5|kn}} | Ship capacity = | Ship crew = 32 | Ship notes = }} |} {{Paranormal}}
'''SS ''Cotopaxi''''' was a [[tramp steamer]] named after the [[Cotopaxi]] stratovolcano. She vanished in December 1925, while en route from [[Charleston, South Carolina]], United States, to [[Havana]], [[Cuba]], with all hands.
==Description== ''Cotopaxi'' is a cargo ship of {{GRT|2351}}. She was built by the [[Great Lakes Engineering Works]], [[Ecorse, Michigan]],<ref name=GLEW>{{cite book|title=The Great Lakes Engineering Works. The Shipyard and its Vessels |publisher=Marine Historical Society of Detroit |location=Detroit |page=311 |url=http://www.mhsd.org/publications/GLEW/indexglew.htm}}</ref> in 1918 for the Clinchfield Navigation Company.<ref name=EP270326>{{cite news |title=Ships and the Sea |newspaper=''Evening Post'' |issue=27 March 1926 |page=27 |url=http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&d=EP19260327.2.161}}</ref><ref name=Ellis/>
''Cotopaxi'' was {{convert|253|ft|m}} long [[between perpendiculars]], with a [[beam (nautical)|beam]] of {{convert|44|ft|m}}. Her steam engine could propel her at {{convert|9.5|kn}}.<ref name=Ellis>{{cite web|url=http://www.ellisisland.org/shipping/Formatship.asp?shipid=4039 |title=Cotopaxi |publisher=Ellis Island |accessdate=10 March 2010}}</ref>
==Final voyage== On 29 November 1925, ''Cotopaxi'' departed [[Charleston, South Carolina]], for [[Havana]], [[Cuba]],<ref name=Times311225/> under Captain W. J. Meyer.<ref name=SN061225>{{cite news |title=Cotopaxi Still Lost; Lighthouse Men Watch; No Word Since Tuesday |newspaper=The Sunday News |issue=6 December 1925 |page=1 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=M4hJAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9gsNAAAAIBAJ&dq=cotopaxi&pg=2089%2C167535}}</ref> She was carrying a cargo of coal and a crew of 32.<ref name=SN061225/> On 1 December, ''Cotopaxi'' radioed a distress call,<ref name=Times311225/> reporting that the ship was listing and taking on water<ref name=EP270326/> during a tropical storm.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19251201&id=DRtiAAAAIBAJ&sjid=sXUNAAAAIBAJ&pg=2892,926927&hl=en Lawrence Journal-World December 1, 1925 .p.1]</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=0klj8wIChNAC&dat=19251208&printsec=frontpage&hl=en The Spokesman-Review December 8, 1925 .p.2 "Think Ship Typhoon Wreck]</ref> The ship was officially listed as overdue on 31 December.<ref name=Times311225>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Mails and Shipping |day_of_week=Thursday |date=31 December 1925 |page_number=18 |issue=44157 |column=D}}</ref>
Despite the last radio transmission indicating that the ship was about to sink, she has since been connected to the legend of the [[Bermuda Triangle]].<ref name="Morton2007">{{cite book|author=Ray Morton|title=Close encounters of the third kind: the making of Steven Spielberg's classic film|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B-ERraCGxkYC&pg=PA311|accessdate=10 March 2011|date=1 November 2007|publisher=Hal Leonard Corporation|isbn=978-1-55783-710-3|pages=311}}</ref>
==In fiction== In the 1977 film ''[[Close Encounters of the Third Kind]]'', ''Cotopaxi'' is discovered<ref name=BBCFilms>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2007/11/26/close_encounters_of_the_third_kind_dvd_2007_review.shtml |title=Close Encounters: 30th Anniversary Ultimate Edition DVD (1977) |publisher=BBC |accessdate=10 March 2011}}</ref>, located in the [[Gobi Desert]], presumably set there by [[Extraterrestrial life|extraterrestrial]] forces.<ref name="Morton2007"/> In a documentary on the making of the film, it is said that the model they used looked nothing like the actual vessel{{cn|date=September 2016}}.
